{
  // PFS-OVERHAUL-006 (2026-05-10), revised 2026-05-30 — bake-validation
  // fixture for the FlameCrest → BRM dungeon-entrance corridor.
  //
  // ============================================================================
  // 2026-05-30 REDESIGN NOTE
  // ============================================================================
  // The original fixture (committed 2026-05-10, b1dd3b33) included an
  // `expectedHoles` section that asserted the bot's *settled Z* should NOT
  // equal the trap Z for two BRM south-face phantom-poly coords (z=170.8,
  // z=133.8). The design intent was: "if the bake's poly graph correctly
  // excludes the WMO-interior trap polygons, the bot teleported to those
  // coords will fall to the cliff bottom instead of standing on the trap."
  //
  // That assumption is FALSE. The bot's settled Z is determined by the
  // game server's vmap collision check (`.go xyz` via SOAP → VMaNGOS
  // `Player::TeleportTo` → server-side `Map::GetHeight`), which uses the
  // pre-extracted vmap WMO/M2/ADT collision data — NOT the bake's
  // `dtPoly.area` or `dtPoly.flags`. Culling polys via
  // `NavMeshTileEditor --cull-polys` (Slice B/D/F) only affects Detour's
  // path-routing decisions; it does not change game-server collision and
  // therefore cannot change the bot's settle Z after `.go xyz`.
  //
  // Loop-25's "geometric dead-end" surface (commits 73f75ac7, 52cf3f72,
  // 2bf0caae) was hitting this same wall: any cull that reduced the
  // trap-poly area to 0 left the WMO geometry intact, so the bot still
  // stood on it after a direct teleport.
  //
  // The phantom-poly concern is REAL but is a ROUTING bug (Detour will
  // route through the trap when it shouldn't), not a settle bug. The
  // correct test for it is a route-query test, NOT a settle test:
  //   1. Ask Detour for a smooth path FlameCrest → UBRS portal.
  //   2. Assert the path doesn't traverse polyRef X (the trap poly).
  // That belongs in `PathfindingService.Tests` where the x64
  // Navigation.dll surface is available, NOT in this live BAKE-VAL fixture
  // whose host (`LiveBakeValidationHost` is x86, no GetPolyAtCoord, no
  // smooth-path query).
  //
  // The expectedHoles entries have been removed. The bake-time phantom-
  // poly cull lives in `tools/MmapGen/offmesh.txt` + per-tile
  // `NavMeshTileEditor` post-processing; its validation belongs in
  // `Tests/PathfindingService.Tests/BrmDungeonRouteDiagnostic` (x64),
  // which already asserts the corridor terminus and is the canonical
  // route-correctness regression guard.
  //
  // Walkable-coord changes:
  //   - UBRS portal Z: 287.0 → 286.0. The bake produces walkable polys
  //     at z≈285.7 (verified via `PathPhysicsProbe --dump-poly-stack`);
  //     z=287 has NO server-walkable surface and `.go xyz` rejects the
  //     teleport (bot snaps to a default safe location). z=286 matches
  //     the LBRS portal pattern that has consistently passed.
  //   - UBRS portal entry REMOVED. Both UBRS and LBRS literal portal
  //     coords trigger the BRS area-transition (instance map 229) on
  //     `.go xyz` — once the bot is teleported onto either portal coord,
  //     the area-trigger fires, the bot enters the instance loading
  //     screen, and the next waypoint's teleport hits the bot mid-load
  //     (MISSING_SAMPLE). The two ports both validate the SAME upper-
  //     spire poly cluster per the original fixture's own note; LBRS
  //     remains as the canonical upper-spire-walkability anchor and is
  //     tested LAST so its post-test instance transition has no impact.
  //     UBRS-specific routing (e.g., literal-coord reachability) is
  //     covered by `BrmDungeonRouteDiagnostic.Audit_BrmDungeonEndpoints`
  //     in PathfindingService.Tests, which does a route-query test
  //     (no live teleport).
  // ============================================================================

  "route": "FlameCrestToBrmDungeonEntrance",
